05894nam a22006735i 9780822391159DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223911597 a10.1515/97808223911592doi  a(DE-B1597)553718  a(OCoLC)1125536646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE78.C15 ǂb F54 2008 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a639/.48321 aField, Les W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAbalone Tales :bCollaborative Explorations of Sovereignty and Identity in Native California /cLes W. Field; ed. by K. Tsianina Lomawaima, Alcida Rita Ramos, Joanne Rappaport, Florencia E. Mallon. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b10 illustrations, 1 map, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarrating Native Histories : 2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Why Abalone? The Making of a Collaborative Research Project -- tI. Artifact, Narrative, Genocide -- t1. The Old Abalone Necklaces and the Possibility of a Muwekma Ohlone Cultural Patrimony -- t2. Abalone Woman Attends the Wiyot Reawakening -- tII. The ‘‘Meaning’’ of Abalone -- t3. Florence Silva and the Legacy of John Boston: Responsibility at the Intersection of Friendship and Ethnography -- t4. Reflections on the Iridescent One -- tIII. Cultural Revivification and Species Extinction -- t5. Cultural Revivification in the Hoopa Valley -- t6. Extinction Narratives and Pristine Moments: Evaluating the Decline of Abalone -- tConclusion. Horizons of Collaborative Research -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor Native peoples of California, the abalone found along the state’s coast have remarkably complex significance as food, spirit, narrative symbol, tradable commodity, and material with which to make adornment and sacred regalia. The large mollusks also represent contemporary struggles surrounding cultural identity and political sovereignty. Abalone Tales, a collaborative ethnography, presents different perspectives on the multifaceted material and symbolic relationships between abalone and the Ohlone, Pomo, Karuk, Hupa, and Wiyot peoples of California. The research agenda, analyses, and writing strategies were determined through collaborative relationships between the anthropologist Les W. Field and Native individuals and communities. Several of these individuals contributed written texts or oral stories for inclusion in the book.Tales about abalone and their historical and contemporary meanings are related by Field and his coauthors, who include the chair and other members of the Muwekma Ohlone Tribe; a Point Arena Pomo elder; the chair of the Wiyot tribe and her sister; several Hupa Indians; and a Karuk scholar, artist, and performer. Reflecting the divergent perspectives of various Native groups and people, the stories and analyses belie any presumption of a single, unified indigenous understanding of abalone. At the same time, they shed light on abalone’s role in cultural revitalization, struggles over territory, tribal appeals for federal recognition, and connections among California’s Native groups. While California’s abalone are in danger of extinction, their symbolic power appears to surpass even the environmental crises affecting the state’s vulnerable coastline.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aGeorge Sr., Merv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHailstone, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLang, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.